               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183908120027"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390812-name-255" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390812-name-255" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390812-name-255" type="surname" value="WIGHTWICK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390812-name-255" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE WIGHTWICK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to Samuel James Nichols, a draper, in Chiswell-street. On the 19th of July, about three o'clock, I missed a piece of printed cotton from inside the door—this is it, and that he had been before convicted.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390812-name-256" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390812-name-256" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390812-name-256" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390812-name-256" type="given" value="RICHARD GEORGE"></interp>RICHARD GEORGE TAYLOR</persName>
                  </hi>. About three o'clock on the 19th of July, I was in Chiswell-street, and saw the prisoner take a piece of print—he ran away—I followed him, and took him in Milton-street—he said he would make it right—I took him to a public-house—he put it down, and ran out, but a policeman took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I was coming from Chiswell-street, and saw this at the door, I took it up and went down Milton-street—Taylor said, "Let us go in here," and he went into the tap-room.</p>
